Economic Performance, Child Mortality, and AIDS Orphanhood: A Global Health Perspective

Author

Mahalakshmi Murugan (A00012659)

INTRODUCTION

Every child deserves a chance to thrive. Yet, millions of children worldwide face preventable deaths due to inadequate healthcare, poor nutrition, and socio-economic challenges. This report highlights child mortality rates and related health indicators, drawing attention to disparities across countries and over time. Using data from UNICEF, we aim to raise awareness and inspire action to improve child survivalÂ ratesÂ globally.

This report analyzes the relationship between economic performance and child Mortality across various countries.

VISUALISATIONS

1. WORLD MAP

Code 
!pip install country_converter > /dev/null 2>&1
import pandas as pd
import geopandas as gpd
import country_converter as coco
from plotnine import ggplot, aes, geom_map, scale_fill_gradient, labs, coord_fixed, theme


EcoData = pd.read_csv("/content/unicef_metadata.csv", usecols=["GDP per capita (constant 2015 US$)", "country", "year"])
Mortality = pd.read_csv("/content/unicef_indicator_1.csv", usecols=["country", "time_period", "obs_value", "sex"])


Mortality_cleaned = (
    Mortality.rename(columns={
        "country": "Country",
        "time_period": "Year",
        "obs_value": "Child Mortality Rate",
        "sex": "Sex"
    })
    .dropna()
)

Mortality_cleaned["Year"] = pd.to_numeric(Mortality_cleaned["Year"], errors="coerce").dropna().astype(int)


average_mortality = Mortality_cleaned.groupby("Country")["Child Mortality Rate"].mean().reset_index()


shape_world = gpd.read_file("/content/world-administrative-boundaries.shp")


shape_world["name_clean"] = coco.convert(names=shape_world["name"], to="name_short")
average_mortality["Country_clean"] = coco.convert(names=average_mortality["Country"], to="name_short")


merged_data = shape_world.merge(average_mortality, left_on="name_clean", right_on="Country_clean", how="left")



mortality_map = (
    ggplot(data=merged_data)
    + aes(fill="Child Mortality Rate")
    + geom_map()
    + scale_fill_gradient2(
    low="#1ABC9C",
    mid="#F4D03F",
    high="#C0392B",
    midpoint=50
)


    + labs(
        title="World Map of Average Child Mortality Rate",
        x="Longitude",
        y="Latitude",
        fill="Avg Child Mortality Rate"
    )
    + coord_fixed()
    + theme_minimal()
    + theme(figure_size=(12, 8))
)

mortality_map.draw()

Across the world, the chances of a childâs survival are dramatically different depending on where they are born. The deep green regions of Sub-Saharan Africa highlight an ongoing crisis: millions of children face life-threatening health conditions due to malnutrition, infectious diseases, and limited access to healthcare.

Meanwhile, the lighter green areas in Europe, North America, and Australia tell a different storyâa world where advanced medical care, sanitation, and early childhood interventions have drastically lowered child mortality rates.

But beyond the colors, this map is a call to action. It reminds us that child mortality is not just a statisticâeach number represents a lost life, a family shattered, and a community in mourning. It underscores the need for policy reforms, humanitarian aid, and healthcare infrastructure to ensure that every child, regardless of location, has the right to survive and thrive.

2. BAR CHART

Code 
import pandas as pd
import geopandas as gpd
from plotnine import ggplot, aes, geom_bar, theme_minimal, labs, coord_flip, scale_fill_manual


world = gpd.read_file("/content/world-administrative-boundaries.shp")





EcoData.rename(columns={"country": "Country"}, inplace=True)


EcoData_with_continent = EcoData.merge(world[["name", "continent"]], left_on="Country", right_on="name", how="left")


continent_grouped = EcoData_with_continent.groupby("continent")["GDP per capita (constant 2015 US$)"].mean().reset_index().dropna()



color_palette = {
    "Oceania": "#4B0082",
    "Europe": "#4169E1",
    "Asia": "#008080",
    "Americas": "#FFD700",
    "Africa": "#C0392B"
}


basic_bar_chart = (
ggplot(continent_grouped, aes(x="continent", y="GDP per capita (constant 2015 US$)", fill="continent"))

    + geom_bar(stat="identity", show_legend=False)
    + scale_fill_manual(values=color_palette)
    + theme_minimal()
    + labs(title="Average GDP per Capita by Continent (2001)", x="Continent", y="GDP per Capita (2001)")
    + coord_flip()
)


basic_bar_chart.draw()

In 2001, the world was shaped by economic inequalities, with some continents thriving and others struggling. Europe led the charge, fueled by industrialization, trade, and infrastructure. The Americas and Oceania followed, benefiting from resource wealth and technological advancements.

Asia, despite rapid industrialization, remained unevenâsome nations surged, while others faced deep poverty. Africa, at the bottom of the chart, reflected systemic economic challenges, driven by colonial legacies, political instability, and resource exploitation.

Fast forward to today, and while Asia has boomed, Africa still fights to close the gap. The chart is a stark reminder of global disparities economic progress is real, but not evenly spread

3. SCATTER PLOT

Code 
import pandas as pd
from plotnine import *


AidsData = pd.read_csv("/content/unicef_indicator_2.csv", usecols=["country", "time_period", "obs_value"])
EcoData = pd.read_csv("/content/unicef_metadata.csv", usecols=["country", "year", "GDP per capita (constant 2015 US$)"])


AidsData.rename(columns={"country": "Country", "time_period": "Year", "obs_value": "AIDS-related Parental Deaths"}, inplace=True)
EcoData.rename(columns={"country": "Country", "year": "Year", "GDP per capita (constant 2015 US$)": "GDP per Capita"}, inplace=True)


AidsData["Year"] = pd.to_numeric(AidsData["Year"], errors="coerce").dropna().astype(int)
EcoData["Year"] = pd.to_numeric(EcoData["Year"], errors="coerce").dropna().astype(int)


AidsData["AIDS-related Parental Deaths"] = pd.to_numeric(AidsData["AIDS-related Parental Deaths"], errors="coerce")


merged_data = AidsData.merge(EcoData, on=["Country", "Year"], how="inner").dropna()


average_deaths = merged_data.groupby("Country")["AIDS-related Parental Deaths"].mean().reset_index()


merged_data = merged_data.merge(average_deaths, on="Country", suffixes=("", "_avg"))


scatter_plot_with_regression = (
    ggplot(merged_data, aes(x='GDP per Capita', y='AIDS-related Parental Deaths_avg'))
    + geom_point(size=0.5, alpha=0.5, color='brown')
    + geom_smooth(method='lm', se=False, color='red', linetype='dashed')
    + ggtitle("GDP per Capita vs Average Parents Died Due to AIDS")
    + xlab("GDP per Capita (constant 2015 US$)")
    + ylab("Average AIDS-related Parental Deaths")
    + theme_classic()
    + theme(axis_text_x=element_text(rotation=45))
    + scale_x_continuous(labels=lambda x: [f'{i:,.0f}' for i in x])
)


scatter_plot_with_regression

The scatter plot presents a compelling relationship between GDP per capita and the number of parents lost to AIDS across different nations. Each green dot represents a country, plotted based on its economic standing and the severity of AIDS-related deaths.

The blue dashed line serves as a trend indicator, showing that as GDP per capita increases, the number of AIDS-related parental deaths decreases. Countries on the left side of the graph, where GDP is lower, tend to have higher mortality rates due to limited access to healthcare, treatment, and awareness programs. Meanwhile, nations on the right, with stronger economies, benefit from advanced medical infrastructure, reducing the impact of AIDS on families

4. TIME SERIES CHART

Code 
import pandas as pd
from plotnine import ggplot, aes, geom_line, theme_minimal, labs, theme, element_text


Mortality = pd.read_csv("/content/unicef_indicator_1.csv", usecols=["country", "time_period", "obs_value"])


Mortality.rename(columns={"country": "Country", "time_period": "Year", "obs_value": "Child Mortality Rate"}, inplace=True)


Mortality["Year"] = pd.to_numeric(Mortality["Year"], errors="coerce").dropna().astype(int)


total_mortality_per_year = Mortality.groupby("Year")["Child Mortality Rate"].sum().reset_index()


time_series_chart = (
    ggplot(total_mortality_per_year, aes(x="Year", y="Child Mortality Rate")) +
    geom_line(color="blue", size=1) +
    theme_classic() +
    theme(
        axis_title_x=element_text(size=16, color="#222222"),
        axis_title_y=element_text(size=16, color="#222222"),
        axis_text_x=element_text(size=12, color="#555555"),
        axis_text_y=element_text(size=12, color="#555555"),
        plot_title=element_text(size=18, color="black")
    ) +
    labs(
        title="Total Child Mortality Cases Over Time",
        x="Year",
        y="Total Child Mortality Cases"
    )
)


time_series_chart.draw()

This line graph, titled âAverage Child Mortality Rate Over Time,â presents the declining trend of child mortality from 1990 to 2020. The y-axis represents the average child mortality rate, ranging from 20 to 35, while the x-axis covers the years from 1990 to 2020.

At the beginning of the period, child mortality was above 30 per 1,000 live births, peaking slightly before beginning a steady decline. Over the next three decades, the trend shows a consistent decrease, with mortality rates falling below 20 by 2020. This suggests significant improvements in healthcare, nutrition, vaccination programs, and overall living conditions for children worldwide.

The smooth downward trajectory highlights global efforts in reducing childhood deaths, emphasizing progress in medical advancements and humanitarian interventions. However, while the decrease is encouraging, the data may also point to regional disparities, meaning some areas have seen slower declines due to conflicts, poverty, or healthcare limitations.

5. DONUT CHART

Code 
import pandas as pd
import geopandas as gpd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt


Mortality = pd.read_csv("/content/unicef_indicator_1.csv", usecols=["country", "time_period", "obs_value"])
WorldData = gpd.read_file("/content/world-administrative-boundaries.shp")[["name", "continent"]]


Mortality.rename(columns={"country": "Country", "time_period": "Year", "obs_value": "Child Mortality Rate"}, inplace=True)


Mortality["Child Mortality Rate"] = pd.to_numeric(Mortality["Child Mortality Rate"], errors="coerce")


Mortality_with_continent = Mortality.merge(WorldData, left_on="Country", right_on="name", how="left").dropna()


continent_mortality = Mortality_with_continent.groupby("continent")["Child Mortality Rate"].sum().reset_index()


colors = ["#FF6384", "#36A2EB", "#FFCE56", "#B58EFF", "#54D896"]


plt.figure(figsize=(8, 8))
plt.pie(continent_mortality["Child Mortality Rate"], labels=continent_mortality["continent"], colors=colors, autopct="%1.1f%%", pctdistance=0.85)
plt.gca().add_artist(plt.Circle((0, 0), 0.65, color='white'))


plt.title("Child Mortality Rate by Continent", fontsize=14, fontweight="bold")
plt.show()

The donut chart presents the proportional distribution of child mortality rates across different continents, providing a visual representation of global disparities in health outcomes for children. The data illustrates significant regional differences, emphasizing the socioeconomic, healthcare, and policy-driven factors that contribute to these variations.

Africa exhibits the highest child mortality rate at 56.8%, highlighting systemic challenges such as limited healthcare access, high rates of infectious diseases, malnutrition, and inadequate maternal and neonatal care infrastructure. Many countries in this region experience constrained medical resources and economic instability, which directly impact child survival rates.

Asia, accounting for 17.4% of global child mortality, demonstrates a mixed trend; while some nations have achieved substantial progress due to economic growth and healthcare advancements, others still struggle with rural healthcare accessibility, poverty, and disease burden.

The Americas (12.1%), Europe (7.1%), and Oceania (6.6%) report significantly lower mortality rates, suggesting stronger healthcare systems, comprehensive vaccination programs, higher living standards, and well-established public health policies that contribute to lower child mortality

CONCLUSION

This analysis highlights the critical disparities in child mortality and economic development across different regions. The relationship between GDP per capita and child mortality underscores the role of healthcare access, socioeconomic stability, and public health interventions in reducing childhood deaths. While global progress has been made, the data reveals persistent inequalities, particularly in Africa and parts of Asia, where mortality rates remain disproportionately high.

Moving forward, targeted investments in healthcare, education, and social infrastructure are essential to narrowing these gaps. The findings emphasize the urgent need for policy reforms, increased humanitarian aid, and sustainable development strategies to ensure equitable child survival rates worldwide.
